(53052, 'Fri Feb 28 16:51:53 EST 2014', 'Fri Feb 28 16:51:53 EST 2014', 'Human Resource Specialist', '<b>The Organization</b><br>The Office of Human Resources is composed of around 150 staff members who serve the University’s employees daily. This is a collaborative environment where teamwork and the sharing of ideas are vital. Our vision is to create an engaging employee experience grounded in a culture of wellbeing and optimal performance.\nThe Affirmative Action Specialist will report directly to the Associate Vice President of Human Resources Compliance, Risk Management, Policies & Procedures. Other members of the team include individuals responsible for Employee and Labor Relations, Compliance and Policy. This is a small, collaborative team that works together to provide proactive, strategic consulting to the University.<br><br><b>Opportunity</b><br>This role will be responsible for the effective coordination and management of OSU’s Affirmative Action program.  This involves program administration, audit administration, outreach to key internal and external partners and project management. The individual in this role will serve as a subject matter expert to HR business partners, leaders and employees on Affirmative Action. This is a new role for the University and is a phenomenal opportunity for an experienced individual to come in and have an immediate impact.<br><br><b>Performance Objectives</b><br><br>•<b>Affirmative Action Plans:</b>  Develop and implement affirmative action plans for OSU.  Partner with HR Business Partners and University leadership to review Affirmative Action Plans, identify areas for improvement and report on progress.  This individual will design solutions, develop and implement processes to achieve Affirmative Action and other HR Compliance objectives, providing sophisticated solutions to a range of internal customers. The individual in this role will be reactive to specific business needs, as well as proactive in terms of improving data flow and the development of key metrics. This position will engage in root-cause analysis and process improvement to resolve problems and enhance the Affirmative Action function.  This individual will also deliver and support the training of Recruiting, HR and managers on the Affirmative Action process, lead the development and deployment of proactive strategies, policies and programs to build a diverse, discrimination-free workplace, reinforce University values, and help drive achievement of objectives. This position is responsible for creating reports used by leadership for strategic decision making, analyzing quantitative data for Affirmative Action planning and other DOL compliance requirements and provides reports for use by the DOL, other government agencies and University administrators.<br><br>\n•<b>Contract Requirements:</b> Develop and implement additional EEO contract requirements, including periodic reviews of HR policies and works with key stakeholders for the creation of new policies.<br><br>\n•<b>Audits:</b>  Serve as the key liaison between the University and government agencies.  Respond to audit requests made by the OFCCP and periodically conducts internal audits to evaluate AAP compliance.<br><br>\n•<b>Projects:</b>  Accountable for contributing new ideas and innovative thinking in identifying solutions.  The individual in this role will be responsible for monitoring regulatory changes and proactively responding to changes in the environment.\n\n', 22),
(53053, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:01 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:01 EST 2014', 'Associate Director', 'Serves as the lead academic advisor managing and working closely with the three members of the advising team responsible for the FTMBA, WPMBA, and Specialized Masters; coordinates efforts to ensure best practices and innovation; serves as the primary academic advisor for the students in the Graduate Minor in Health Sciences; builds partnerships with colleges where there might be opportunities to create dual degrees; serves as the liaison between Fisher''s recruiting and admissions team and student services; responsible for the donor stewardship for all of the graduate degree programs.', 37),
(53054, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:13 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:13 EST 2014', 'Office Admin Associate', 'Manages and oversees daily administrative functions of the administrative office of the Center for Research & Transdisciplinary Scholarship (CRTS) and provides administrative support for the Associate Dean for Research & Transdisciplinary Scholarship  (ADR); coordinates the ADR''s appointments and calendar; makes all travel arrangements for a variety of national and international meetings; conveys directives and information; researches and analyzes materials to aid the ADR in decision-making and planning; independently drafts, composes, and responds to correspondence; support Grants Manager with grant submissions (updating CV''s, Biosketches, gathering Letters of Support, staff reminders), progress reports, and renewals; reviews and authorizes expenditures for travel, basic supplies and supplies for the biomedical labs; develops and prepares fiscal and administrative process reports; coordinates weekly CRTS meeting schedule, sets agenda, prepares minutes, coordinates follow up items with appropriate personnel; develops, organizes and oversees special projects, events, and assignments; determines and organizes agendas; prepares PowerPoint presentations and posters; assists with development and maintenance of administrative, fiscal and research databases and web-based materials; manages the solicitation and receipt of letters of support for PI grant applications; coordinates the annual T32 external advisory committee meeting.', 38),
(53055, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:14 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:14 EST 2014', 'Program Coordinator', 'This position contributes to the international dimension of The Ohio State University by providing program support to the Global Gateways of The Ohio State University; coordinates day-to-day operations and program activities for the Gateways; serves as a liaison and point of contact on programs and activities for Gateway offices overseas and Ohio State academic units; researches and tracks Ohio State collaborations in Gateway regions; builds and manages relationships with the Office of International Affairs and Academic and Support Units, including but not limited to Colleges, Professional Schools, Regional Campuses, Student Life, Legal Affairs and the Global Gateways; shares information with the central communications unit of the Office of International Affairs, which is responsible for publicizing and communicating the range of international activities in which Ohio State is involved; plans, schedules, and executes events to further the goals of the Global Gateway office; serves as the Ohio State program manager for the Universitas21 relationship.', 18),
(53056, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:14 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:14 EST 2014', 'Director-00', 'The Director of Operations will be responsible for the direct oversight and management of the day-to-day internal operations of the Student Financial Aid office. This individual must be a relationship builder as the primary components of the job are providing leadership and direction to managers and staff within the office and serving as a liaison with other departments, colleges and extended campuses. This position regularly interacts with all areas of Enrollment Services, colleges and academic support units at Ohio State, regulatory and governmental agencies, software vendors, both internal and external auditors, and university compliance officers.<BR><BR>\n\nThe Director of Operations manages the internal operations of the Student Financial Aid office in compliance with all federal, state, and NCAA regulations, as well as institutional policies, in order to authorize and coordinate $1 billion in total financial assistance, including loans, scholarships, grants and Federal Work Study, to 49,000 students in a manner consistent with the university’s mission. This individual will work closely with the Executive Director of Student Financial Aid to plan and implement the future direction of the office. The Director of Operations will also act as the primary liaison and work with the Director of the Student Service Center (SSC) to ensure that the SSC staff is providing quality financial aid information and customer service to students and parents.<BR><BR>  \n\n<b>Position Environment</b>\nThe Director of Operations will report directly to the Executive Director while providing direct and indirect supervision to 52 staff members. This individual will work with colleges, the University Bursar, and other OSU departments, in addition to collaborating with financial aid communities in the Ohio/Midwest area.<BR><BR>\n\n<b>Performance Objectives</b>\nSpecifically, this position will be responsible for:\n1. Providing leadership, oversight and direction to the office on a daily basis.\n2. Managing internal operations of the Student Financial Aid office, directly supervising four Associate Directors and indirectly supervising Assistant Directors of all functional areas, including performance planning and management.\n3. Providing oversight to systems analysis personnel in the development of computer applications and the SIS system, compliance and training personnel in the development of staff training programs, and scholarships and funds management personnel in the administration of all university merit and donor scholarship funds and the reconciliation of all federal and state financial aid programs.\n4. Collaborating with the Executive Director in planning and implementing the current and future direction of the office.\n5. Staying current with statewide, regional and national trends that may affect Ohio State and the university’s constituencies.\n6. Directly overseeing salary/budget administration and assisting the Executive Director in establishing budget priorities.\n7. Acting as a liaison with colleges and university departments, secondary school local communities and the general public, and representing the office with key university communities and task forces.\n8. Communicating effectively with a diverse audience.', 19),
(53057, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:15 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:15 EST 2014', 'Program Manager', 'Acts independently as the program manager for an assigned portfolio of advancement events. Demonstrates and applies a level of consistency and a standard of excellence to designing and implementing events for the purpose of expanding awareness of, advocacy for, engagement in and giving to Ohio State. Partners with colleagues in The Ohio State University Alumni Association, University Development, University Communications and colleges/units. ', 5),
(53058, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:15 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:15 EST 2014', 'Program Coordinator', 'Provides support for the development team focusing on hematologic cancers and special events at The Ohio State James Cancer Hospital and Solve Research Institute.', 5),
(53059, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:16 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:16 EST 2014', 'Fiscal Associate', 'This position supports the international dimension of The Ohio State University by providing support to the fiscal/procurement functions for study abroad programs in a fast-paced, deadline-driven, team-oriented environment.  Job duties include but are not limited to: accurate and timely processing of study abroad program expenditures, financial and managerial accounting for study abroad programs, financial recordkeeping and balancing of program revenues and expenditures, and program fee calculations. The fiscal associate works with faculty and staff program organizers, travel agents, and the OSU travel office to process high-volume travel procurement requests and payment requests using electronic and paper based systems in compliance with OSU policies and procedures.  Provides training to faculty and staff on expenditure policies, procedures, and recordkeeping. This position requires the use of excellent interpersonal communication skills, representing the office in a professional and courteous manner in both personal and written interactions. Requires extensive knowledge of OSU expenditure policies, travel policies, and Procurement and Group Extended Travel Card Policies. Requires advanced knowledge of MS Word and Excel and accurate and efficient data entry skills. This position also supports general office duties for the Business Operations team including but not limited to Procurement Card checkout, laptop checkout, deposits, and building coordinator.', 18),
(53060, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:19 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:19 EST 2014', 'Program Coordinator', 'Provides support for the major gift function of the Athletics Development Office; responsible for the planning, organizing and execution of all special events from induction to completion; assists by documenting policies, procedures, best practices, and templates for event planning and execution; responds to ad hoc requests from University Development Donor Relations as appropriate; provides excellent customer service to inquiries from staff, donors, university administrators and other constituents, maintaining a high level of confidentiality; manages or executes other projects as assigned.', 5),
(53061, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:21 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:21 EST 2014', 'Custodial Worker', 'The Custodial Worker maintains a safe and clean environment in and around assigned Student Life residence halls, offices and other properties for student residents, guests and staff; responsible for day-to-day cleaning as well as other housekeeping duties involved with special housing operations; cleans rooms, offices and public areas; cleans most flat surfaces, furniture, windows, vents, and light fixtures; may count, issue, and receive linen; operates basic electrical cleaning equipment; maintains floors and carpets, moves furniture, removes trash, clears snow, and cleans building entrances and walkways; reports any damage or theft discovered in work area; may be asked to respond to emergencies; climbs ladders and scaffolding.', 16),
(53062, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:24 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:24 EST 2014', 'Systems Specialist-A&P', 'Serves as technical support for University Advancement and responds to requests for technical assistance in person, via phone or electronically; responsible for proper incident and problem management processes; logs all service desk interactions and redirects problems to appropriate resources; participates in the creating of FAQs and the Knowledge Base; assists in the development and updating of system documentations and standards for desktops, laptops and printers and advises customers regarding system software and hardware enhancements; requires good communication skills with the ability to work independently.', 5),
(53063, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:26 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:26 EST 2014', 'Staff Assistant', 'Provides administrative support to the Technology Commercialization Licensing team; oversees operational and administrative functions and activities; defines and evaluates problems; initiates and gains support for improvements in new and modified program procedures; maintains internal databases and facilitates recordkeeping for licensing team marketing and company engagement; contributes to optimal business solutions and excellent customer satisfaction through effective written and verbal communication with university faculty, researchers and administrators; assists in driving licensing team portfolios through marketing processes and scheduling of companies; creates and facilitates written correspondence; liaison between Technology Commercialization office and constituents; establishes and maintains relationships with university faculty, researchers and administrators; manages high profile relationships on behalf of the Licensing team; develops correspondence, drafts presentations and prepares reports; maintains team members'' schedule and calendar of events and arranges travel; responsible for significant meeting planning; ensures appropriate action is taken to meet department goals and guidelines; represents office to outside organizations, community and customer base; special projects as assigned.', 14),
(53064, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:27 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:27 EST 2014', 'Open Faculty Search', 'The overall role of the Regional Director, Operations, is to provide leadership to the Extension operations within the Southwest region comprised of 19 counties, including all matters affecting personnel, finance, public relations and business operations. As Associate Chair, the Regional Director works closely with the Department Chair in carrying out responsibilities associated with promotion and tenure development/direction. The Regional Director, Operations, works collaboratively with the OSU Extension administrative cabinet and Extension employees, numerous advisory committee members, volunteer stakeholders, public officials and other community leaders and volunteers in the region. Internal and external applicants are required to accurately self-disclose all criminal convictions when they apply. Final candidate offer is contingent upon the university''s verification of credentials and other information required by law and/or university policies or practices based upon a criminal background check. ', 25),
(53065, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:27 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:27 EST 2014', 'Dining Utility Worker', 'The Utility Worker maintains a clean, sanitary, and safe environment in a food service operation serving students, staff, and guests of the university; operates and sets up dishwashing equipment: cleans dish return systems and area; disposes of all trash and food waste; stocks and/or supplies dispenser equipment and food items; cleans and sets up beverage, soft serve and other service equipment; cleans kitchen equipment; ensures the refrigerators are clean and in accordance with prescribed standards; cleans and maintains kitchen and serving equipment; washes windows and light fixtures; maintains floor cleanliness by sweeping and mopping.  ', 26),
(53066, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:27 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:27 EST 2014', 'Asst Director of Development', 'The Associate Director of Development for the Fisher College of Business develops and implements short- and long-term plans to secure major gifts from alumni, friends, volunteers and entities in support of the colleges and university''s missions, objectives and priorities as set by the unit directors, college dean and development’s senior vice president. Focus of the position is to build a pipeline of major gift prospects for the college in a college culture of constant change with exciting, cutting-edge programs. A person who loves the hunt and enjoys uncovering and building relationships with friends of the university will thrive in this position. The Development team in the Fisher College of Business relies on many strong partnerships with colleagues across campus and takes pride in personal accountability. This collaborative environment encourages and rewards independently motivated individuals who are not easily deterred and have dogged determination. The successful individual in this position will have proven ability to make a large number of cold calls and personal visits and cultivate prospects, moving them along the prospect continuum to eventually secure major gifts.', 5),
(53067, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:29 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:29 EST 2014', 'Lecturer', 'The Ohio State University at Mansfield is accepting applications for a full-time Lecturer in Spanish. The appointment will be effective  Autumn Semester, 2014, and will involve teaching various courses constituting the university''s three-semester sequence of General Education courses intended to develop oral and written competencies in Spanish.  Additional courses taught in English which involve Hispanic cultural study or comparative literature may be part of the person''s teaching load, depending upon background and interest. The possibility exists for additional teaching during summers. This appointment, while not tenure eligible, is renewable. The M.A. in Spanish is required, although the Ph.D. is preferred. Successful Spanish teaching at the college level is also preferred. ', 24),
(53068, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:32 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:32 EST 2014', 'Traffic Control Officer', 'As a member of the Transportation and Traffic Management team, this position is responsible for controlling vehicular and pedestrian traffic on the Columbus campus; directs traffic during roadway construction and repair, special events and other occurrences as needed; closes off road access and reroutes traffic to improve flow of vehicles and pedestrians around campus as needed for construction sites, special events or other occurrences; conducts non-injury traffic accident investigations and processes related paperwork; provides assistance and information to faculty, staff, students and visitors. Ensures motorist and pedestrian compliance with campus rules and regulations; enforces University policy regarding bicycle usage on campus; issues warnings and/or citations as necessary; removes, impounds and transports to storage bicycles as needed; monitors traffic equipment including barricades, A-frames, cones, signs, caution tape, sign stands and other materials; confirms set up/tear down of materials required for events; conducts traffic surveys; assists in training of other officers. ', 21),
(53069, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:33 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:33 EST 2014', 'Employee & Labor Relations Consultant', '<b>The Opportunity</b><br>The Ohio State University, one of the nation’s leading public universities, is seeking a flexible and resilient Employee & Labor Relations Consultant to serve in the Office of Human Resources’ Employee and Labor Relations department. The position requires a consultative and collaborative individual capable of building solid relationships throughout the university and at all levels of the organization.<br><br>\nWith a service-oriented approach, the individual will provide human resource consultation and services with specific emphasis on employee and labor relations as a member of a consulting team. These duties include providing information, training and consultation to college and departmental administrators, managers, human resource professionals, faculty and staff regarding a variety of ER/LR issues from performance management to the interpretation and implementation of federal/state regulations and OSU HR policies. Similarly, the successful Employee & Labor Relations Consultant will come to know their customer groups so well that they will be able to proactively identify potential areas of risk and develop and implement action plans for resolution.<br><br>\nUltimately, the day to day duties of the position calls for an individual who is prepared to conduct complex investigations and who recognizes the personal and organizational value of this process for the institution. While investigations can be challenging at times, they are vital to the achievement of the university values. The successful individual in this role will display a high level of comfort and resilience with fluctuating and shifting situations and, at times, will experience a heavy workload. The role will also be a rewarding one as the successful candidate will form strong relationships with his/her customer base resulting in the creation of a sustained trusted advisory role. In addition, the Employee & Labor Relations Consultant will partner with their teammates and the larger OSU community to achieve the unit and university strategic goals. The successful candidate will be a self-starting team player, able to maintain objectivity while performing their duties and who values integrity, diversity and the importance of having fun along the way. In the first 90 days, the successful candidate will understand their role in the organization and how the work they perform supports the larger mission of the university.<br><br><b>Performance Objectives</b><br>Specifically, this position will be responsible for:\n1. Investigating discrimination and sexual harassment complaints, workplace violence allegations, and other cases of a complex nature; and issuing written reports to the unit and the employee with specific action steps, as appropriate. \n2. Providing confidential, proactive and objective consultation to various constituencies.\n3. Collaborating to develop and implement effective practices that result in a healthy culture.\n4. Reviewing departments’ adherence to guidelines, procedures and employment laws and regulations.\n5. Identifying and analyzing specific employee and management actions regarding employee relations policies, procedures and documentation.\n6. Integrating work/life and diversity principles into consultation practices and providing training regarding these and other employee relations issues.\n7. Interpreting bargaining unit agreements while establishing and maintaining satisfactory labor-management relationships.\n8. Assisting with problem/conflict resolution before escalation to formal grievance or corrective action.\n9. Serving as Hearing Officer for corrective action and/or grievance meetings and developing and issuing appropriate written responses.\n10. Leading meetings involving the Crisis Assessment Team.\n11. Analyzing trends to find actionable, pragmatic solutions to employee relations issues.\n12. Assisting in the development and/or revision of employee relations programs, policies and tools that align with university objectives of promoting a high performance culture with an emphasis on creativity, flexibility, coaching, feedback and accountability.', 22),
(53070, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:35 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:35 EST 2014', 'Director-00', 'As a member of senior team in Administration & Planning (A&P), provides leadership and strategic direction for all aspects of internal and external public relations, communications and marketing efforts to support A&P and its business units (TTM, FOD, PPARE, UniPrint, & Public Safety); develops, coordinates and implements the communications strategy on reputational or high level public relations, public safety or crisis management issues within A&P with an eye to maintaining an effective balance between broad university and A&P objectives and the needs of specific departments and programs; produces detailed communications plans and serves as primary resource for executive level talking points, fact sheets and message development; responsible for the management and associated budget of the shared services unit including staffing and processes to ensure alignment with university mission and branding; ensures appropriate staffing levels and metrics associated with providing efficient and effective communications, public relations and marketing services; oversees the development  and implementation of marketing/communications plans, tools, and tactics including multimedia, website and social media strategy and development; measures and evaluates the outcomes; strategically coordinates and integrates communications efforts across A&P units as appropriate; writes, edits, and develops presentations; ensures A&P leaders/staff have tools needed for everyday communications; ensures A&P communications, public relations and marketing efforts are integrated and aligned with university branding and communications direction and serves as liaison with University Communications and communications colleagues around the university, including strong working relationships with all areas of University Communications, Student Life, Athletics and Wexner Medical Center communications counterparts; collaborates with university media relations as needed; develops strategy and responds to media inquiries as appropriate; represents A&P and advises A&P leaders on public relations matters; completes and participates in other initiatives/ projects as needed.', 20),
(53071, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:37 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:37 EST 2014', 'Security Officer', 'Provides physical security for assigned university facilities. Performs customer service functions such as answering directional questions, providing escorts to nearby campus locations, and providing assistance to disabled patrons; patrols buildings and grounds, and monitors fire and security alarms; works in security control room monitoring CCTV cameras, answering telephone, dispatching security officers and maintaining radio contact; administers first aid; operates fire extinguishers; investigates and reports on fires, crimes, unusual incidents, complaints, injuries and accidents.', 48),
(53072, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:38 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:38 EST 2014', 'Coor-Student Financial Aid Reg', 'Provides counseling services and support in the Marion Campus Financial Aid Office and for our Delaware partnership location; counsels enrolled and prospective students, families, and other users; coordinates financial aid training for students and staff employees; researches and resolves problems; provides service on and off campus; makes presentations; participates in meetings and committees; collaborates with Advancement team regarding donor stewardship; completes special duties as assigned. ', 33),
(53073, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:38 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:38 EST 2014', 'Director-A5', 'Serves as the Chief Information Officer for the College of Food, Agricultural and Environmental Sciences; duties to include defining strategy and providing leadership for central and distributed College IT staff, College IT infrastructure and architecture, including related interfaces with other university and external systems, application development, networks, outsourcing, academic, research, outreach and business unit support, reengineering business processes, and customizing solutions to support teaching, research, outreach and administration; tracks a broad range of emerging technologies to determine their maturity and applicability to the College and its educational, research and outreach missions; assesses the relative impact of emerging technology to strategic needs and interprets their meaning to senior organization leadership team; understands the College''s collective IT competencies and their value to the units individually and to the College as a whole; determines long-term College IT needs and develops strategy for systems development, acquisition and integration; leads College technology planning and policy development, aligning a current knowledge and future vision of technology and systems with the College''s goals; partners with College leadership and departments to provide overall leadership and strategic planning for the College''s IT budget, ensuring the IT budget supports the College''s strategic plan; closely partners with departmental Chairs and school Directors, College leadership, various committees and internal stakeholders on strategies, planning, procurement and other areas of common interest; serves as member of the leadership team for the College and influences strategic decisions regarding the use of technology; and represents the College''s IT interests and ambitions to the university''s OCIO, as well as intramural and extramural peer organizations.', 32),
(53074, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:38 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:38 EST 2014', 'Program Coordinator', 'The Ohio State University Libraries is currently seeking applications for a Non-Roman Languages Coordinator within the Collections and Technical Services Division to coordinate, plan, develop, evaluate, and supervise Non-Roman Languages cataloging within the University Libraries. Successful candidates will possess experience planning and overseeing cataloging in several foreign languages, experience supervising, delegating and motivating a team, and strong organizational, analytical, and problem solving skills. Under the supervision of the Head of Cataloging the position will lead the Non-Latin Languages Section and will be responsible for:<BR><BR> \n\nManaging and supervising 6.5 staff in the Non-Roman Language Section, including hiring and training of staff and students assistants; working closely with the OSU Language and Area Studies department defining workflows and  solving cataloging issues; develops and maintains collegial relationships with key library departments particularly Acquisitions, Information Technology, and Preservation and Reformatting departments; performing original and complex copy cataloging of materials representing all levels of difficulty, all subjects and all formats according to RDA, LCRIs, LCSH, LC classification and MARC formats; participating in the NACO, SACO, and BIBCO components of the Program for Cooperative Cataloging (PCC) and performing authority work in accordance with local and national standards and guidelines; solving problems related to obsolete or incorrect information appearing in bibliographic and holdings records and well as assisting staff and student assistants in solving problems and achieving high level of accuracy; keeping current with revisions to cataloging rules and trends, bringing revisions to the attention of the Head of Cataloging and assisting in the implementation of changes in the department, including the potential services and technologies; preparing monthly report of the Non-Roman Section activities; maintaining the Non-Roman Languages website and blog.', 10),
(53075, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:39 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:39 EST 2014', 'Coord-Planning And Scheduling', 'The role of the Operations Planner is to improve staff productivity and work quality by anticipating and eliminating potential delays through planning and coordination of labor, parts, material, and equipment access; works with maintenance shop supervision and crew leads to develop long and short term plans for equipment repair and maintenance based on plans handed down by Facilities Operations and Development administration and corrective work initiated through the Preventive Maintenance program; works closely with the Maintenance Engineering group to improve quality of PM and planned work requests, including procedures, equipment inventories, parts lists and replacement data captured in the CMMS system; work in conjunction with the zone staff to construct daily, weekly and monthly planning schedules when workload permits; stays in coordination with stakeholder through continual communication with first line supervision, the planning group and materials coordination; collaborates with other Maintenance Planners, Maintenance Engineers, and support groups to insure standardized maintenance processes.  ', 3),
(53076, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:40 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:40 EST 2014', 'Systems Developer/Engineer', 'Provides IT support to the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering (ECE) and The Simulation Innovation and Modeling Center (SIMCenter); support includes systems administration, hardware maintenance, networking, printing, installing and debugging 3rd party software systems, maintaining and writing custom scripts, user consultation; works with College of Engineering and OSU IT communities in support of common projects and tools; creates, analyzes and plans complex IT solutions to address identifiable needs; researches IT industry advancements for future applications; responds to and remediates IT security events/threats; administers the department''s and center''s desktops, workstations, and servers; oversees network operations; completes end user requests and incidents through resolution; recommends and orders hardware/software while recognizing cost-effectiveness; manages and maintains equipment inventory of all capitalized and non-capitalized items; ensures compliance with university and college policies, initiatives, and mandates.', 31),
(53077, 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:41 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 01:05:41 EST 2014', 'Head Coach', 'Develops, directs, and coaches an intercollegiate spirit squad program.  Conducts all practices and rehearsals.  Instructs athletes in the proper technique for fundamentals of dance choreography for routines and cheerleading including tumbling, stunting, etc; responsible for the development of all routines and performances in cooperation with assistant coaches and choreographers as part of a comprehensive game atmosphere initiative; coordinates participation and performances at home football games and other sports as requested; manages requests for cheerleaders and Brutus participation in department, University, community and private events; manages all administrative aspects of the spirit squad including scheduling, travel, equipment needs, budget, and staffing; manages all college-prep clinics, cheerleader recruiting and selection process, appearances, and competitions.  Monitors academic progress of spirit squad.  Participates in development activities to promote the program.', 29),
(53079, 'Sat Mar 01 14:58:15 EST 2014', 'Sat Mar 01 14:58:15 EST 2014', 'Disability Case Manager', 'Are you looking for the next step in your career?  Do you want to be a part of team that helps improve the lives of the people that they serve?  The Ohio State University’s Integrated Disability department is a robust team that maintains a <b>proactive, fast-paced approach to case management</b>. The department services the entire university and Wexner Medical Center, so our Disability Program Managers provide consultative services to an <b>unparalleled variety of employees</b>. This diversity fosters a <b>continuous expansion of knowledge</b> about a variety of professions and work environments.\n\nThe team is comprised of <b>critical, forward-thinking team-players</b>, who are challenged every day with new opportunities to improve the lives of Ohio State University employees.   Since its inception, our innovative Transitional Work program has maintained an extremely high return-to-work rate, which has resulted in savings to the university in excess of 13 million dollars.  The following information further details the Disability Program Manager role and the opportunity to impact the university, but the message is simple - the Integrated Disability team''s <b>commitment to excellence</b> in service permeates every aspect of what we do, and we are looking for the next team-member to <b>join our mission</b>.<br><br><b>The Opportunity</b><br>Integrated Disability lies within the Office of Human Resources at The Ohio State University.  The department assists faculty and staff in linking with appropriate disability benefits, including Short and Long Term Disability, workers'' compensation, and state retirement systems.  Additionally, Integrated Disability assists with the evaluation and provision of reasonable accommodations, oversees the disability separation process, coordinates medical leaves, remain-at-work and return-to-work services, unemployment benefits, and other programs for employees that become disabled. \n\nUnder the direction of the Team Lead for Transitional Work, the Disability Program Manager provides proactive, individualized case management services for employees with occupational and/or non-occupational illnesses and injuries. The position is charged with determining an employee’s temporary or long-term accommodation needs to assist them in achieving employment goals.  The Disability Program Manager coordinates efforts with various entities, including medical providers, managed care organizations (MCO), disability carriers, OSU ancillary services, third party administrators (TPA), and state agencies to assure continuity of services. Along with overseeing daily claim activities, the Disability Program Manager drafts and implements return-to-work plans and recommendations for employees and their employing departments, and provides vocational rehabilitation services for workers’ compensation claims. While maintaining consistent contact with the employee, the Disability Program Manager works collaboratively with managers, Human Resource Professionals, the Americans with Disabilities Act Coordinator, legal services and employee and labor relations to ensure successful execution of transitional work agreements and accommodation plans. \nThe Disability Program Manager utilizes a sophisticated case management system to aid in case documentation and reporting.  The extensive documentation of cases and the development of valuable reports help to ensure compliance with university, state and federal policies. In addition to documenting individual claims data, the Disability Program Manager provides disability trending, return-to-work statistics and OSHA metrics to business partners across the university and medical center on a regular basis. This individual also provides formal trainings to their assigned departments related to Integrated Disability services including disability benefits and accommodations.<br><br><b>Position Environment</b><br>This position reports to the Team Lead for Transitional Work within Integrated Disability. The Integrated Disability department is under the direction of the Manager of Integrated Disability and Unemployment and the Associate Director of Compliance Risk Management, Policies and Procedures. A successful candidate will possess strong organizational skills and be able to address multiple projects at the same time.  A high volume of cases coupled with outside project work can be expected.   In addition to the external collaborations with vendors and university departments highlighted above, there is also a strong collaborative culture within the department of Integrated Disability.  In addition to the Disability Program Manager role, the Integrated Disability team is also comprised of Leave Administrators, Claims Managers, a Job Developer, and an onsite Physical Therapist.', 27),
(53081, 'Mon Mar 03 09:12:30 EST 2014', 'Mon Mar 03 09:12:30 EST 2014', 'Systems Developer/Engineer', 'The Ohio Supercomputer Center (OSC) provides high-performance computing (HPC) services for The Ohio State University researchers and industrial clients. This Engineer position in the Supercomputer Systems group will provide technical expertise to design, develop and operate our large-scale HPC production environment. This engineer will develop solutions for OSC clients (including installing and upgrading software), monitor, troubleshoot and maintain HPC services and respond to emergency situations involving system problems, downtime and security breaches.', 35),
(53082, 'Mon Mar 03 09:13:47 EST 2014', 'Mon Mar 03 09:13:47 EST 2014', 'SR Systms Dev/Eng-Sap', 'The Ohio Supercomputer Center (OSC) provides high-performance computing (HPC) services for university researchers and industrial clients. This Manager position in the OSC Web and Interface Applications Group will lead the specification, design and development of software applications leveraging OSC services. This covers a broad range of services including OSC OnDemand, science gateways, and industrial services like AweSim, and HPC interface apps for tablet and smartphone platforms.', 34),
(53089, 'Mon Mar 03 16:20:45 EST 2014', 'Mon Mar 03 16:20:45 EST 2014', 'Locksmith 1', 'Installs, maintains and repairs doors, locks and associated hardware; installs, maintains and repairs locks, locking devices, exit devices, closers and doors, cuts keys, repairs and installs lock cores and cylinders; maintains key cutting, key code and lock change records; maintains daily time records; requisitions materials.Assists other trades as needed; adheres to all safety practices and procedures; cleans and maintains work areas and equipment; attends meetings; assures properly completed documentation; provides a high level of customer service; communicates to customers, coworkers and supervision via written, electronic and verbal methods and devices; performs other duties as assigned. ', 3);
